<m0>U<m2><ql>
<m0>p on Madison Avenue, the expensive suits shell out $30,000 for an hour of seminar wisdom from Faith Popcorn.<ep>
    After all, it was she who saw a nation hunkering amid sofa cushions and four-head VCRs and pronounced America ``cocooning.'' She who knew before the first top popped that new Coke lacked fizz. She who Fortune magazine dubbed ``the Nostradamus of marketing.''<ep>
    But at the moment, on Northwest 187th Avenue in North Miami, she's offering her insights<m0> . . . for free.<m0><ep>
    Mike Woulfe, a big, burly guy, stands by his big, burly motorcycle, a $15,000 BMW R-1000 RT. While interviewing Popcorn on the Miami stop in a tour for her new book, <m0>Clicking, <m0>($26, HarperCollins), Woulfe, news director at WINZ radio, had let on that he sometimes flirts with the notion of getting into the cycle biz.<ep>
    So now here's Popcorn pondering the gleaming machine. Woulfe fidgets, like maybe he's worried about getting billed for these three minutes. She smiles, nods her head and says this: ``Egonomics. Fantasy Adventure. Down Aging. Pleasure Revenge.''<ep>
   In Popcorn-speak, this means: Great idea.<ep>
   And Woulfe suddenly, seriously, is considering jumping careers. When the trendiest of trend gurus says, ``Go for it,'' <m1> <m0>people listen.<ep>
   ``God, you know, she's <m2><ql>
<ql>
PLEASE SEE  POPCORN,  4C<qr>
<m4>--7.472 inches ( 45p )--from start of measuring to here--<m2><ql>
